	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The Super Game boy 2 has link capability LED's and some new borders as far as I know.<br /><br />No Game Boy Colour compatibility though.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Wed Feb 26, 2014 8:37 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Super game boy adapter for the Snes</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The difference is that SGB2 has the Game Link port plus a second oscillator for the SGB CPU to eliminate the slight speedup that the first SGB applied. The first SGB divided the Super NES's 945/44 = 21.477 MHz master clock by 5 to produce a 4.2955 MHz DMG clock, which is slightly faster than the 2^22 Hz = 4.1943 MHz clock on an actual Game Boy.<br /><br />Exactly replicating the video rendering model of the Game Boy Color, including mid-screen changes, would require more video memory bandwidth than the Super NES has. The Wide Boy 64 accessory (limited release) plays Game Boy Color carts, as does the Game Boy Player accessory for Nintendo GameCube.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


